WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.240
Hello, everyone.

00:00:02.240 --> 00:00:04.000
My name is Dane.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.300
Thanks for coming to my talk.

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:08.580
How has everyone been enjoying the conference so far?

00:00:08.580 --> 00:00:09.220
Has it been good?

00:00:09.220 --> 00:00:09.990
I've been loving it.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.870
So, today's the last day of the conference, and

00:00:14.870 --> 00:00:19.520
we have heard a lot of really interesting talks from a lot

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:21.000
of different people over the past couple days.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:24.160
And there's been some really interesting and weird references that have

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.000
been made, too, like some really cool ones.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Like we had Aaron yesterday talking about kelp.

00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:32.000
We had Blaine talking about cheese making.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.010
And then we had Lawrence talking about K-pop and the

00:00:35.010 --> 00:00:36.000
K-pop fandom.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.560
I just love that all these references happened at this conference so

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:40.000
far.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.400
It especially makes me feel good because it makes what I'm

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:46.000
about to talk about seem not quite as crazy.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.340
Because my talk is titled "From Toilets to Moss

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:53.460
: The Future of Social Media is Weird and Not for Everyone

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:56.290
." So, to kick things off, I want to introduce

00:00:57.010 --> 00:01:00.000
myself a little bit for those who don't know me.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.440
I am not Three Moss in a Trenchcoat, despite

00:01:04.510 --> 00:01:07.460
what my bio on Blue Sky says, unfortunately, though sometimes

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:08.000
I wish that I was.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.170
I was born and raised in Appalachia around the

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:17.940
exact same time that the World Wide Web came into existence.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.650
So, I've kind of grown up alongside of the Web

00:01:21.660 --> 00:01:24.000
and seen it grow as I have.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.160
I am an artist, I'm a tech worker, and

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:30.590
I created the app Anasota, which some of you

00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:32.000
may have seen or tried recently.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.630
But my background is in communications, content, social media,

00:01:35.630 --> 00:01:37.000
and things like that.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.590
But I've been working in the decentralized Web space actually for

00:01:41.590 --> 00:01:45.000
the past five years, before Blue Sky even existed.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:47.870
I was Blue Sky user number 1216, so I've

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:51.000
been around in this community for quite some time.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.930
I've had a few breaks here and there, but I

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:59.000
really sort of came back and became more active in 2024 again

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.810
and started making things on the App Protocol.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
But as a result of my personal interests and professional obligations,

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.580
I have been relatively chronically online for various stretches of my

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:15.000
life.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.660
And that has, along with the fact that I grew up

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:23.240
alongside the Internet, it's really caused me to both have

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:26.820
kind of a love-hate relationship with the Internet.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.110
I love the Internet for, I love Twitter, I love

00:02:30.110 --> 00:02:33.990
the old Internet, I loved all these different things.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.100
But it's also been hard to watch how they've impacted

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:39.000
my life, both good and bad.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And it's also been hard watching Twitter die.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.270
It's been hard watching so many things happen to so many

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:48.410
of these apps and websites that we love and sort of continually

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:50.000
getting worse and worse in a lot of ways.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.610
But yeah, it has impacted me in amazing ways, though

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:55.000
.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.750
Like, I've gotten multiple jobs just from being on Twitter

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:58.000
.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.000
I met my partner online.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.010
But yeah, it definitely had these negative impacts of impacting society

00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:09.000
negatively, impacting my mental health negatively.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.480
And I think what I ultimately realized as a result of all

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:15.440
that was that, yeah, these apps and a lot of

00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:19.420
the web is not necessarily really built for me, necessarily for

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:20.000
anyone in particular.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.650
It's often built for, you know, big tech shareholders

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:24.000
.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.000
It's built for advertising.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:26.990
It's built for extraction, all these different things.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And it's more like we, or at least me,

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.100
I've been able to make these things work in spite of

00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:33.990
all these things.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.000
But even then, there have been so many limitations.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.380
As a result of this, I feel like there's a

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:45.040
temptation to look back, especially for folks like me who grew

00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:48.580
up alongside the early internet, there's a temptation to look

00:03:48.850 --> 00:03:50.510
back at it and be like, I wish we could go

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:51.000
back there.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:52.990
I wish we could go and return to the past.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.620
And I think that's like a very, I get that

00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:58.000
sentiment.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:03:59.920
But I also think that it's like, it's kind

00:03:59.920 --> 00:04:02.440
of misguided and maybe even a little dangerous at times

00:04:02.510 --> 00:04:06.040
of like, like we don't ultimately want to, I

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:08.000
don't think we should make, try to make the internet

00:04:08.190 --> 00:04:09.000
great again.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.650
I think that, I think, and if we can't

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:16.700
do that, and we shouldn't do it, at least

00:04:16.700 --> 00:04:20.100
that mindset, I guess the question that emerges for me is

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:23.000
what should we do and what should that future look like?

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.060
And after working in the decentralized web space for the past five

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:32.500
years, it's definitely given me some ideas and thoughts about

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:37.000
what I think might be trying to emerge from this cocoon

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:37.000
.

00:04:38.850 --> 00:04:42.390
And, and I say trying because I think despite like all

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:46.800
of our excitement about the atmosphere and the things that we're

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:50.500
building and creating here, none of it really is a guarantee

00:04:50.970 --> 00:04:51.000
.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:52.850
Like we're, we're sort of right now trying to

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:54.000
make this thing happen.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.300
And it's uncertain, it's uncertain if it will happen

00:04:58.300 --> 00:04:59.000
or not.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And I think it's important to keep that in mind.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:03.990
Cause it's going to take a lot of work.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.290
But it's kind of like, you know, if some

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:09.550
of you may have followed me and, and watch some of

00:05:09.550 --> 00:05:13.000
my live streams on stream place last year, I was,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
I was raising monarch butterflies and I was streaming that.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.610
And you could see the butterflies emerging for their cocoons and

00:05:18.610 --> 00:05:20.000
all the chrysalises.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.620
Um, and, but the reality is some of them didn

00:05:22.660 --> 00:05:25.010
't make it, you know, like I had, I

00:05:25.050 --> 00:05:28.850
think 12 different butterflies and I think four or five of them

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:29.940
didn't make it.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Um, yes.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:32.820
I mean, in the same way, like this, uh

00:05:32.850 --> 00:05:34.650
, what we're doing here, uh, it's not

00:05:34.650 --> 00:05:36.000
guaranteed to succeed.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.210
Uh, we've made a lot of progress, I think

00:05:38.210 --> 00:05:40.710
over the past, I mean, even the past six months

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:42.000
, it's been pretty cool to see what's been happening

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
and the number of people that are here today.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.290
Um, but, uh, so let's, let's

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:50.000
, let's dive a little bit more.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
I just realized I forgot to advance my slides here.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:54.700
Um, let's, let's dive a little bit more

00:05:54.850 --> 00:05:57.150
into what the future might look like through the lens of some

00:05:57.230 --> 00:05:59.000
of the things that I've been working on in the atmosphere

00:05:59.000 --> 00:05:59.990
over the past 12 months.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.710
Um, so to get started, uh, the very first

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:06.970
thing I made was in 2024, it was literally a simple

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:09.760
tool I built just for me, uh, to go through

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:13.660
my, my post archive and choose whether I wanted to keep

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:16.360
something or delete something and sort of like that KonMari

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:16.940
fashion.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.030
Um, and this very much was, well, I have

00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:24.410
some, well, I have some background in doing some software

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:28.610
stuff and like, um, you know, making websites and

00:06:28.610 --> 00:06:29.000
HTML and CSS.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.990
I had never actually made a web app before.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.290
So this was like the first thing I ever did in that

00:06:33.490 --> 00:06:34.000
vein.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.990
Um, and it was here in the atmosphere.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.290
Uh, the second thing I did was this platform called cred

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:39.500
.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:40.000
blue.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.550
It was kind of a weird, fun experiment in understanding the

00:06:43.550 --> 00:06:46.920
data model of the app protocol better, understanding what was possible

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:49.990
, just like testing things and seeing what would happen.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.120
And it was just a way to like create a, a

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:55.000
, a social score based on someone's profile.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.460
Um, so that was, that was the second thing I

00:06:57.460 --> 00:06:58.000
made.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:06:59.860
Uh, the next thing I made was this, uh,

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:02.000
more of an art project and creative thing.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
It was a dynamic avatar that runs off of my iPhone.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.650
And what happens is every day, every hour, my avatar

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:13.840
automatically updates to match the, sort of the way the sky

00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:16.460
, the sky gradient looks, um, wherever I am in

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:17.000
my local time.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:18.760
So if you've seen my, if you see my avatar

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:21.140
on the feed and you've seen that changes colors, that

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:23.000
's, that's exactly what it's doing.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:24.570
It's been doing that now for, I guess, over

00:07:24.610 --> 00:07:24.990
a year.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.990
It's been running nonstop right off my iPhone.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.050
Um, and then after that I made this weird thing called

00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:32.000
flushes.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.990
Uh, this happened about a year ago.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.770
Uh, right around, I think exactly coinciding with last

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.000
year's conference.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.620
Um, it was basically an experiment to try to figure out

00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:43.000
one, how do I make an app view?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:44.000
I've never made an app view.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:45.990
I don't even really know what an app view is.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.270
Um, so it was better, it was going one step

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:52.000
further and learning more about, uh, the app protocol.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.650
And honestly asking this question of what, can, can,

00:07:55.650 --> 00:08:00.000
can you easily make a new social network or a social platform

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:00.000
really easily?

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:01.990
And how quickly can you do that?

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.650
And this was made in like two days and, you know

00:08:05.970 --> 00:08:07.060
, it, it went kind of like, uh, viral

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:11.100
within the atmosphere community and people started posting and using it a

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:11.990
bunch the first few days.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.280
Um, it was just interesting to see what, what happened

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:15.000
there.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:16.650
And it, but it taught me a lot about, uh

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:18.000
, I guess what was possible.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:19.870
Um, and then after that, I, uh, I

00:08:19.870 --> 00:08:22.670
