like 50,000 unique people.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
It was really cool to see it spreading around the community.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.130
Um, so yeah, these are some of the things that

00:15:26.130 --> 00:15:28.150
I've like, I've been working on and making in

00:15:28.230 --> 00:15:29.000
the atmosphere.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:30.990
And they've taught me a lot.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.220
And I, I think there's some ideas and themes that

00:15:33.220 --> 00:15:34.900
emerged, um, that I want to share and talk about

00:15:34.980 --> 00:15:38.680
, uh, that are basically lessons of what I think potentially

00:15:38.680 --> 00:15:39.000
might happen in the future.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:40.990
Or it might is already happening.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.290
Um, uh, let's see, let me scroll down

00:15:44.010 --> 00:15:45.000
through my notes.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.490
Um, so first of all, um, the future is

00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:51.000
decentralized, right?

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:52.000
Do we think that's true?

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.450
Um, so I've been working in the open web,

00:15:54.450 --> 00:15:57.000
like I said, for around five years now.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:58.620
And when I got here, like that was the theme is

00:15:58.850 --> 00:16:00.000
decentralization is the answer.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:01.000
This is the key.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.000
This is the thing we're trying to do here.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:03.990
Um, and it makes sense, uh, initially.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
Um, I still believe that it is somewhat true.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.650
Um, but I also think that it's a little misleading

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:12.000
.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.340
Um, I think that it's actually kind of the wrong

00:16:15.390 --> 00:16:16.000
goal.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:17.680
Um, it's, uh, it's, it's

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:21.000
not really much to be chased after in and of itself.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.430
It's something that we're doing and using a quality that

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:27.590
we're trying to use to obtain a specific goal or state

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:27.990
.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.440
Um, but it's also kind of an illusion because,

00:16:32.510 --> 00:16:35.840
um, it's a very ambiguous word that has so many

00:16:35.930 --> 00:16:39.000
different meanings in different contexts, in different perspectives.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And there's questions of is the atmosphere decentralized?

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:43.990
Is activity pub decentralized?

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
What about Noster?

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And all these different things.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.280
Um, and there's so many criteria which you can measure

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:50.000
that by.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.630
Um, and it ends up just becoming debates that we have

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:54.000
endlessly on blue sky.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:55.970
I'm sure many of you probably, I know I have

00:16:55.970 --> 00:16:58.000
participated in some of those debates.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.630
Um, but it's, it's an illusion in the

00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:05.730
sense that no matter how decentralized you think you can make something

00:17:05.730 --> 00:17:08.000
, ultimately there's always something underneath.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
That is not decentralized.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:13.000
That you can't really escape.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.150
Uh, if, if Noster, if Atmosphere

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:19.390
, all these different things are fully decentralized in this utopic

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:19.990
way.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.810
Uh, at the end of the day, there's,

00:17:21.850 --> 00:17:24.940
uh, an internet service provider that can shut off your access

00:17:24.940 --> 00:17:26.000
to the internet.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:27.990
A government that can shut off your access to the government.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.750
And at that point, it's like, well, it

00:17:29.850 --> 00:17:31.000
doesn't really matter.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.020
Um, but also, it, there's a tendency with

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:37.100
, uh, decentralization to think that, oh, I

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:37.990
can separate myself from everyone else.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.000
I can become independent.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
I can control things.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
I can do what I want.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.000
I can, yeah, all these different things.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.530
But ultimately, it's, um, we tend to forget

00:17:46.530 --> 00:17:49.990
just how, or even aware of just how, like,

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:51.000
interconnected everything really is.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.270
Um, there's this great term, uh, by a

00:17:54.010 --> 00:17:56.170
Vietnamese Buddhist monk, uh, I mean, Thich N

00:17:56.180 --> 00:17:57.000
hat Hanh.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.990
Uh, he coined this term interbeing.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.630
And it's really about this idea of, like, focusing

00:18:02.630 --> 00:18:06.700
and trying to better understand and be aware of just how our

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:10.000
, our existence is so intertwined with everything else.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.260
Um, and it's just not really actually possible to,

00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:18.000
like, separate ourselves, uh, fully.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:19.990
Um, so I like to keep that in mind.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.330
Um, and I think that it can potentially help us ref

00:18:23.390 --> 00:18:26.990
ocus to maybe some going beyond decentralization.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.830
Maybe we don't want to lose that phrase completely, but

00:18:30.010 --> 00:18:32.170
what a lot of people are trying to ask when they're

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:35.350
thinking about these things and users are asking or feeling is these

00:18:35.410 --> 00:18:36.990
questions of, like, can I leave this thing?

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Can I, can I build something here?

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
Can I, can I make this my own?

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.640
Um, and I think words and concepts like interoperability

00:18:43.860 --> 00:18:47.190
, autonomy, and malleability are actually a lot more

00:18:47.190 --> 00:18:50.050
helpful, potentially, because there's lots of ways that you

00:18:50.100 --> 00:18:51.000
can achieve those things.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.660
Um, and malleability, specifically, is one I

00:18:54.980 --> 00:18:56.000
really love.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.290
And it's funny, because I was, as I was

00:18:59.010 --> 00:19:01.010
preparing this talk, I, of course, had no idea

00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:03.100
what Jay was going to announce the other, you know,

00:19:03.100 --> 00:19:05.000
just yesterday or what she was planning.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.290
But it does really fit into what I had planned to talk

00:19:07.430 --> 00:19:08.000
about.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.280
There's this, uh, really great, uh, essay

00:19:10.430 --> 00:19:13.060
by Ink and Switch, uh, that they released, I

00:19:13.100 --> 00:19:15.840
forget, maybe sometime last year, called Malleable Software

00:19:15.840 --> 00:19:16.000
.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
And I love this essay.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.720
Um, it's very long, but it has some great

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:21.000
quotes, like this one.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.470
Um, the original promise of personal computing was a new kind

00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:26.060
of clay, a malleable material that users could res

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:30.230
hape at will, but instead we got appliances built far away

00:19:30.240 --> 00:19:32.000
, sealed, and unchangeable.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:33.580
Um, and for me, this, I don't know

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:35.000
, this really resonates.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:36.580
And this makes me feel like, yeah, this is an

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:38.000
apt description of what happened.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.890
Um, and I do think that as a result of some

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:47.000
things that, some new technologies and communities that are evolving now

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.190
and converging, I think that it makes some malle

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:52.420
able software much more of a potential reality than it ever has

00:19:52.420 --> 00:19:53.000
been in the past.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.150
Um, specifically, I think that the atmosphere we're participating

00:19:57.230 --> 00:20:00.460
in here with the app protocol, combined with what some of

00:20:00.510 --> 00:20:03.710
what Jay was talking about, these sort of agentic workflows

00:20:03.710 --> 00:20:07.460
with LLMs, they really can begin to bring down

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:11.500
a lot of barriers to entry and allow people who previously probably

00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:15.000
wouldn't have tried or attempted to make their, their,

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:19.000
their digital environments their own or make software experiences themselves.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:20.760
Um, it makes it, um, yeah, it makes

00:20:20.850 --> 00:20:22.000
it a lot more possible.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.900
Um, you know, the atmosphere gives people, like,

00:20:24.970 --> 00:20:28.000
a foundation that they can easily take and build upon.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.770
It gives you a social graph, it gives you pre-

00:20:31.010 --> 00:20:34.170
existing content, it gives you identities, um, that you

00:20:34.170 --> 00:20:34.990
don't have to rebuild from scratch.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.170
It would, it's make, it, it's what

00:20:37.170 --> 00:20:40.200
makes, uh, something like Flushes possible that I

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:41.990
could do in two, two days.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:45.010
Um, uh, another great quote from that essay that I

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:47.000
want to highlight is this one.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.290
It says, "Everyone deserves the right to evolve their digital

00:20:49.430 --> 00:20:50.000
environments.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.350
It's an important way to fulfill our creative potential and maintain

00:20:52.950 --> 00:20:56.440
a sense of agency in a world that is increasingly defined in

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:59.170
code." Um, and I think this is really what I

00:20:59.170 --> 00:21:02.530
've been trying to do and what I think the atmosphere has

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:05.800
helped enable me to do, is it's allowed someone like

00:21:05.850 --> 00:21:09.650
me who does not have necessarily the resources, the ability to

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:13.000
create an entirely new social network myself, but it allows me

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.060
to engage with that digital environment in a way that feels more

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:21.100
at home to me or fits better with my own needs and

00:21:21.100 --> 00:21:21.940
style.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.080
Um, this brings me to, like, the second,

00:21:24.080 --> 00:21:27.070
the second point I want to talk about, which is this

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:31.000
idea that I have of the client being the content.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:34.650
And I'm sure many of you reference, understand this reference

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:36.880
, which is a, uh, a remix of a quote

00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:40.350
by Marshall McLuhan back in the '60s with his

00:21:40.350 --> 00:21:44.000
book, "The Medium is the Message." Um, and

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.440
to tie this a little bit back into moths, um

00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:49.150
, moths are interesting for a lot of reasons, but

00:21:49.150 --> 00:21:52.100
they're very different, obviously, from many other creatures and

00:21:52.100 --> 00:21:53.000
even, obviously, humans.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.290
Um, moths have, uh, you know, compound

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:59.270
eyes that I think range from anywhere from, like, 200

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:02.000
to 200,000, uh, 20,000 facets.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:07.000
Um, their, uh, antennae are incredibly sensitive.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:11.000
Uh, they can detect chemicals and things within the air.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:12.990
Um, and they help them fly.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.550
They have, uh, hearing organs, which are kind of

00:22:15.550 --> 00:22:17.000
like ears, but not quite like ears.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:20.000
But they can detect, like, ultrasonic frequencies.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.160
Um, so they're, they have these, like,

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:25.590
sensory organs that allow them to experience the world in a unique

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:26.000
way.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:29.260
Um, and there's this term called, I think it

00:22:29.260 --> 00:22:30.000
's pronounced umwelt.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.170
It's a, it's based on a German word,

00:22:32.170 --> 00:22:33.000
I believe.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.440
Um, but it means the specific way in which an organism

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.990
, which organisms of a particular species perceive and experience the world

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:43.320
, shaped by the capabilities of their sensory organs and perceptual

00:22:43.390 --> 00:22:44.000
systems.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.320
So, I think that, uh, this is very,

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:51.310
uh, apt for what we're experiencing now in this era

00:22:51.310 --> 00:22:53.940
of malleable software that is coming into existence.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:58.540
Um, because previously, uh, previously in the old era

00:22:58.540 --> 00:23:01.840
of social media, we had, uh, things like Facebook

00:23:01.930 --> 00:23:05.330
, which was one user interface designed in Silicon Valley by,

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:09.180
you know, tech giants and things like this, serving billions

00:23:09.180 --> 00:23:13.500
of people all over the world from different communities and contexts with

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:14.990
different needs and wants and desires.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:19.440
And it was basically kind of forcing them to experience the digital

00:23:19.510 --> 00:23:21.990
world in this one particular way.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.670
Um, and then I think a good example of this is

00:23:25.010 --> 00:23:27.420
going back to this is there's two different ways that you

00:23:27.420 --> 00:23:28.000
can view data.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:29.980
